<h1>Introduction to the Na=C3=AFve Bayes Algorithm</h1>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
The simplest solutions are usually the most powerful ones, and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.kdnuggets.com/2020/06/naive-bayes-algorithm-everything.html">Na=
=C3=AFve Bayes</a> is a good example of that. Despite the advances in Machi=
ne Learning in the last years, it has proven to not only be simple but also=
 fast, accurate, and reliable.</p><div class=3D"kdnug-c41720905c569adfa447b=
c60d9c7b64c kdnug-after-first-paragraph" id=3D"kdnug-c41720905c569adfa447bc=
60d9c7b64c"></div>
<p>It has been successfully used for many purposes, but it works particular=
ly well with natural language processing (NLP) problems.</p><div style=3D"p=
adding-bottom:180px;padding-top:20px;" class=3D"kdnug-bd485aa83eb8d4b82876e=
4fe19221470 kdnug-in-content-1" id=3D"kdnug-bd485aa83eb8d4b82876e4fe1922147=
0"></div>
<p>Na=C3=AFve Bayes is a probabilistic machine learning algorithm based on =
the&nbsp;<strong>Bayes Theorem</strong>, used in a wide variety of classifi=
cation tasks. In this article, we will understand the Na=C3=AFve Bayes algo=
rithm and all essential concepts so that there is no room for doubts in und=
erstanding.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_1_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h1>Bayes Theorem=
</h1>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem is a simple mathematical formula used for calculatin=
g conditional probabilities.</p>
<p><strong>Conditional probability</strong>&nbsp;is a measure of the probab=
ility of an event occurring given that another event has (by assumption, pr=
esumption, assertion, or evidence) occurred.</p>
<p>The formula is: =E2=80=94</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"p=
resentation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/=
2000/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E=
%3C/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-1.j=
pg"></p>
<p>Which tells us: how often A happens&nbsp;<em>given that B happens</em>, =
written&nbsp;<strong>P(A|B)&nbsp;</strong>also called posterior probability=
, When we know: how often B happens&nbsp;<em>given that A happens</em>, wri=
tten&nbsp;<strong>P(B|A)</strong>&nbsp;and how likely A is on its own, writ=
ten&nbsp;<strong>P(A)</strong>&nbsp;and how likely B is on its own, written=
&nbsp;<strong>P(B).</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote><p>
<font size=3D"+1">In simpler terms, Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem is a way of find=
ing a probability when we know certain other probabilities.</font>
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h2>Assumptions M=
ade by Na=C3=AFve Bayes</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
The fundamental Na=C3=AFve Bayes assumption is that each feature makes an:<=
/p>
<ul>
<li>independent</li>
<li>equal</li>
</ul>
<p>contribution to the outcome.</p>
<p>Let us take an example to get some better intuition. Consider the car th=
eft problem with attributes Color, Type, Origin, and the target, Stolen can=
 be either Yes or No.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_3_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h1>Na=C3=AFve Ba=
yes Example</h1>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
The dataset is represented as below.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-2.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Concerning our dataset, the concept of assumptions made by the algorithm=
 can be understood as:</p>
<ul>
<li>We assume that no pair of features are dependent. For example, the colo=
r being =E2=80=98Red=E2=80=99 has nothing to do with the Type or the Origin=
 of the car. Hence, the features are assumed to be&nbsp;<strong>Independent=
</strong>.</li>
<li>Secondly, each feature is given the same influence(or importance). For =
example, knowing the only Color and Type alone can=E2=80=99t predict the ou=
tcome perfectly. So none of the attributes are irrelevant and assumed to be=
 contributing&nbsp;<strong>Equally</strong>&nbsp;to the outcome.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;The assumptions made by Na=C3=AFve Bayes are=
 generally not correct in real-world situations. The independence assumptio=
n is never correct but often works well in practice.&nbsp;<strong>Hence the=
 name =E2=80=98Na=C3=AF&gt;ve=E2=80=99.</strong></p>
<p>Here in our dataset,&nbsp;<strong>we need to classify whether the car is=
 stolen, given the features of the car</strong>. The columns represent thes=
e features and the rows represent individual entries. If we take the first =
row of the dataset, we can observe that the car is stolen if the Color is R=
ed, the Type is Sports and Origin is Domestic. So we want to classify a Red=
 Domestic SUV is getting stolen or not. Note that there is no example of a =
Red Domestic SUV in our data set.</p>
<p>According to this example, Bayes theorem can be rewritten as:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-3.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>The variable&nbsp;<strong>y</strong>&nbsp;is the class variable(stolen?)=
, which represents if the car is stolen or not given the conditions. Variab=
le&nbsp;<strong>X&nbsp;</strong>represents the parameters/features.</p>
<p><strong>X</strong>&nbsp;is given as,</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-4.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Here&nbsp;<code>x1, x2=E2=80=A6, xn</code>&nbsp;represent the features, =
i.e they can be mapped to Color, Type, and Origin. By substituting for&nbsp=
;<strong>X&nbsp;</strong>and expanding using the chain rule we get,</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-5.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Now, you can obtain the values for each by looking at the dataset and su=
bstitute them into the equation. For all entries in the dataset, the denomi=
nator does not change, it remains static. Therefore, the denominator can be=
 removed and proportionality can be injected.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-6.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>In our case, the class variable(<strong>y</strong>) has only two outcome=
s, yes or no. There could be cases where the classification could be multiv=
ariate. Therefore, we have to find the class variable(<strong>y)</strong>&n=
bsp;with maximum probability.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-7.png"=
><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Using the above function, we can obtain the class, given the predictors/=
features.</p>
<p>The posterior probability&nbsp;<strong>P(y|X)</strong>&nbsp;can be calcu=
lated by first, creating a&nbsp;<strong>Frequency Table</strong>&nbsp;for e=
ach attribute against the target. Then, molding the frequency tables to&nbs=
p;<strong>Likelihood Tables</strong>&nbsp;and finally, use the Na=C3=AFve B=
ayesian equation to calculate the posterior probability for each class. The=
 class with the highest posterior probability is the outcome of the predict=
ion. Below are the Frequency and likelihood tables for all three predictors=
.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-8.png"=
></p>
<p>Frequency and Likelihood tables of =E2=80=98Color=E2=80=99</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-9.png"=
></p>
<p>Frequency and Likelihood tables of =E2=80=98Type=E2=80=99</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-10.png=
"></p>
<p>Frequency and Likelihood tables of =E2=80=98Origin=E2=80=99</p>
<p>So in our example, we have 3 predictors&nbsp;<strong>X</strong>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-11.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>As per the equations discussed above, we can calculate the posterior pro=
bability P(Yes | X) as :</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-12.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>and, P( No | X ):</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-13.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Since 0.144 &gt; 0.048, Which means given the features RED SUV and Domes=
tic, our example gets classified as =E2=80=99NO=E2=80=99 the car is not sto=
len.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_4_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h1>The Zero-Freq=
uency Problem</h1>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
One of the disadvantages of Na=C3=AFve-Bayes is that if you have no occurre=
nces of a class label and a certain attribute value together then the frequ=
ency-based probability estimate will be zero. And this will get a zero when=
 all the probabilities are multiplied.</p>
<p>An approach to overcome this =E2=80=98zero-frequency problem=E2=80=99 in=
 a Bayesian environment is to add one to the count for every attribute valu=
e-class combination when an attribute value doesn=E2=80=99t occur with ever=
y class value.</p>
<p>For example, say your training data looked like this:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-14.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>????(TimeZone=3D????????|Spam=3D????????????)=3D10/10=3D1</p>
<p>????(TimeZone=3D????????|Spam=3D????????????)=3D0/10=3D0</p>
<p>Then you should add one to every value in this table when you=E2=80=99re=
 using it to calculate probabilities:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-15.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>????(TimeZone=3D????????|Spam=3D????????????)=3D11/12</p>
<p>????(TimeZone=3D????????|Spam=3D????????????)=3D1/12</p>
<p>This is how we=E2=80=99ll get rid of getting a zero probability.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;<br>
</p><center><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmln=
s=3D'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=
=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt=3D"XXXXX" width=3D"100%" class=3D"p=
erfmatters-lazy" data-src=3D"https://i.ibb.co/8Pm3kCs/bayes-nagesh-16.gif">=
<br>
<font size=3D"-1"><a href=3D"https://medium.com/@sanjeethboddi/naive-bayes-=
algorithm-from-scratch-715d7cc0de53" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Ima=
ge credits</a></font></center><br>
&nbsp;<p></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_5_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h1>Types of Na=
=C3=AFve Bayes Classifiers</h1>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_6_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h2><strong>1. Mu=
ltinomial Na=C3=AFve Bayes Classifier</strong></h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
Feature vectors represent the frequencies with which certain events have be=
en generated by a&nbsp;<strong>multinomial distribution</strong>.&nbsp;This=
 is the event model typically used for document classification.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_7_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h2><strong>2. Be=
rnoulli Na=C3=AFve Bayes Classifier</strong>:</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
In the multivariate Bernoulli event model, features are independent boolean=
s (binary variables) describing inputs. Like the multinomial model, this mo=
del is popular for document classification tasks, where binary term occurre=
nce (i.e. a word occurs in a document or not) features are used rather than=
 term frequencies (i.e. frequency of a word in the document).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_8_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad   adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><h2><strong>3. Ga=
ussian Na=C3=AFve Bayes Classifier:&nbsp;</strong></h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
In Gaussian Na=C3=AFve Bayes, continuous values associated with each featur=
e are assumed to be distributed according to a&nbsp;<strong>Gaussian distri=
bution (</strong><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distributi=
on" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Normal distribution</a><strong>)</st=
rong>. When plotted, it gives a bell-shaped curve which is symmetric about =
the mean of the feature values as shown below:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-17.jpg=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>The likelihood of the features is assumed to be Gaussian, hence, conditi=
onal probability is given by:</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter perfmatters-lazy" role=3D"pres=
entation" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns=3D'http://www.w3.org/200=
0/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C=
/svg%3E" width=3D"100%" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-18.png=
"><br>
&nbsp;</p>
<p>Now, what if any feature contains numerical values instead of categories=
 i.e. Gaussian distribution.</p>
<p>One option is to transform the numerical values to their categorical cou=
nterparts before creating their frequency tables. The other option, as show=
n above, could be using the distribution of the numerical variable to have =
a good guess of the frequency. For example, one common method is to assume =
normal or gaussian distributions for numerical variables.</p>
<p>The probability density function for the normal distribution is defined =
by two parameters (mean and standard deviation).</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><center><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmln=
s=3D'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20width=3D'100%'%20height=3D'0'%20viewBox=
=3D'0%200%20100%%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt=3D"Figure" width=3D"100%" class=3D"=
perfmatters-lazy" data-src=3D"/wp-content/uploads/bayes-nagesh-19.png"><br>
<font size=3D"-1"><p></p>
